postcontent: We have for auction a consecutive serial-numbered pair of P95 9mm caliber pistols. The stainless P95 Manual Safety model pistol was first introduced as “NEW” in the 2001 Ruger® Firearms Catalog. The serial numbers of these pistols are 314-42397 and 314-42398 and the testfire date for both is February 2, 2001. The pistols have never been fired beyond normal testing during manufacture. The pistols’ slides are made of Terhune Anticorro stainless steel and feature nearly indestructible resin grip panels and custom compounded polymer frames. These manual safety model pistols incorporate a manual ambidextrous lever that, when engaged, prevents firing unless the lever is in the “fire” position. The KP95 pistols will each be shipped in a gray plastic pistol case along with one 10-shot magazine, magazine loader, and appropriate instruction manual. An original 2001 Ruger firearms catalog is also included with this auction. The pistols are being sold “as is,” and the purchaser assumes all liability for their safe and proper ownership, storage, use, and resale. title: For Sale:  Winchester M1 Garand Rifle, Very Rare Barrel
postcontent: Only produced during WWII by Winchester this one is in remarkable condition for an issued rifle and has a very interesting story to tell.From our observation and the use of Scott Duffs Book and Guide we have been able to identify many parts in this rifle as original Winchester.The barrel was made by Springfield but has a Winchester proof visible when the op rod is locked back. There are no Springfield proof marks meaning that Springfield never assembled it and only the drawing number, date and steel batch code are SA. This surprised us and after a few phone calls to elderly collectors and authorities on the Garand we were assured that although unusual and very rare this is a product of sharing or loaning of parts to keep production output unbroken by delays. Parts sharing or use of other manufacturers parts was more common place than most people think but was very poorly documented and it is likely that only a few hundred at the most may have been built this way and even fewer would have survived post war rebuilds. The bore has strong lands and grooves and has been through the rebuild process as there is hard chrome around the gas port. The Gas Plug is a single slot type which is period correct and is most likely a replacement as the blued finish is almost 100%.
